column6: Based on current prices and "wisdom of the crowd"

Interest rates have been held artificially low for a long time due to the housing collapse. Interest rates are finally being corrected by the Federal Reserve Board. Depository institutions now have the opportunity to scalp some profits from the remaining prime rate borrowers in the market. Banks attempting to prevent sticker shock is the major reason prime rates haven't jumped quicker after the recent 25 basis point rate hike and rising rate forecast by the Fed. One basis point per week over the next couple weeks seems reasonable to avoid potential borrower sticker shock but create urgency to buy among prime borrowers.
WoC 50% so I'll move up to 25 instead of 15, but not enough data here, only 14 forecasters playing with this Q. And 35 forecasts made. Need hundreds.
